#compdef docrawl
# ============================================================================
# docrawl - polite documentation-site crawler:
#            HTML -> Markdown (Rust, MIT)
#
# Author : neur0map
# Upstream: https://github.com/neur0map/docrawl
# crates : docrawl (binary: docrawl)
#
# `docrawl` is a same-origin documentation-site crawler
# that downloads HTML pages, extracts the main content
# section (via configurable CSS selectors), and converts
# the result to clean Markdown for ingestion by docs
# pipelines / static site generators / LLM training
# corpora. It handles rate limiting, concurrency, robots
# .txt, asset downloading, sitemap discovery, and resume-
# from-frontier-cache - the operational shape of "I want
# to scrape this docs site for an LLM context" without
# the ad-hoc fragility of a one-off wget script.
#
# Usage:
#   docrawl <URL> [FLAGS]
#
# Flags (clap derive Parser):
#       --all                    crawl whole same-origin
#                                 site (ignores --depth)
#       --depth <N>              max link depth from start
#                                 (default 10)
#   -o, --output <PATH>          output root (site folder
#                                 is created inside)
#       --concurrency <N>        parallel fetch workers
#                                 (default 16)
#       --rate <N>               global requests/second
#                                 (default 10)
#       --host-only              restrict scope to exact
#                                 origin (scheme+host+port)
#       --external-assets        allow downloading images
#                                 from other domains
#       --allow-svg              permit saving SVG images
#       --max-pages <N>          stop after N pages
#       --selector <CSS>         preferred content selector
#                                 (repeatable)
#       --exclude <REGEX>        URL exclusion regex
#                                 (repeatable)
#       --timeout-minutes <N>    graceful shutdown after N min
#       --resume                 resume from persisted
#                                 frontier in cache
#       --no-assets              skip downloading images
#                                 / assets (fastest)
#       --fast                   preset: higher rate /
#                                 concurrency + no assets
#       --silence                no status / progress output
#       --update                 self-update from crates.io
#   -h, --help                   print help
#   -V, --version                print version
#
# The html5ever lane is built on `scraper = "0.24"`
# (declared verbatim at upstream Cargo.toml HEAD), the
# canonical Rust HTML-querying crate by Causal Agency +
# the rust-scraper working group - github.com/rust-
# scraper/scraper, 2400+ stars. scraper is a thin
# ergonomic facade over `servo/html5ever` (the spec-
# compliant HTML5 parser extracted from the Servo browser
# engine, 1700+ stars) + `causal-agent/selectors` (the
# CSS-Selectors-Level-4 implementation also from Servo).
# `scraper::Html::parse_document()` walks the input string
# through html5ever's tokenizer + tree builder producing
# a fully-typed DOM tree, then `scraper::Selector::parse`
# compiles a CSS selector string into a runtime matcher
# that can iterate over matching elements.
#
# docrawl uses scraper in `src/extract.rs` to pull the
# main-content region from each crawled HTML page:
# `scraper::Html::parse_document(html_body)` then
# `Selector::parse(".main, article, .content, main")` (or
# the user-supplied `--selector` value) then iterate +
# extract text. The Markdown conversion is delegated to
# `fast_html2md` which itself uses html5ever for its
# secondary parse pass.
#
# Why html5ever as the canonical Rust HTML parser? It is
# the only Rust HTML5 parser that targets the WHATWG HTML
# Living Standard tree construction spec byte-for-byte
# (vs. ad-hoc parsers that approximate the spec). When
# scraping real-world web pages with malformed markup
# (missing close tags, mismatched nesting, character
# entity quirks), html5ever's tree-builder applies the
# spec's error-recovery rules identically to what a
# WHATWG-compliant browser would do - so the parsed DOM
# matches what a browser would render.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 242 :: HTML5 parsing (WHATWG-spec-compliant DOM
#              construction + CSS selectors)
# Round 1424 :: Rust slot 1 of 4 :: OPENS Axis 242
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis
# (proposed):
#   Rust    : servo/html5ever (+ scraper) - the WHATWG
#                                            spec-compliant
#                                            HTML5 parser
#                                            extracted
#                                            from Servo,
#                                            with scraper
#                                            as the
#                                            ergonomic
#                                            facade
#   Go      : golang.org/x/net/html        - the Go core-
#                                            team-
#                                            maintained
#                                            HTML5
#                                            tokenizer +
#                                            tree builder
#                                            in the
#                                            golang.org/
#                                            x/net subrepo
#   TS/Node : inikulin/parse5              - the WHATWG-
#                                            spec-compliant
#                                            HTML5 parser
#                                            used by
#                                            cheerio,
#                                            jsdom, and
#                                            Angular SSR
#
# HTML5 parsing is a clean spec-bound axis - the WHATWG
# HTML Living Standard defines the tokenizer state machine
# (~80 states) + the tree construction insertion modes
# (~25 modes) byte-for-byte. Compliant parsers produce
# bit-identical DOM trees for the same input HTML, modulo
# implementation-specific extensions to the DOM node
# types. All three lanes pass the html5lib test suite
# (the spec's official conformance corpus).
#
# Structural commentary on the canonical-library origins:
#   - servo/html5ever (Rust): extracted from Mozilla's
#     experimental Servo browser engine; the same parser
#     that ships in Firefox's Gecko codebase via the
#     stylo subsystem
#   - golang.org/x/net/html (Go): maintained by the Go
#     core team in the `golang.org/x/net` subrepository
#     (same import-path namespace as net/http2 + net/
#     idna); intentionally minimal API surface
#   - inikulin/parse5 (Node): pure-JS WHATWG-spec parser
#     by Ivan Nikulin; the de-facto Node HTML5 parser,
#     bundled into cheerio (the Node "jQuery for the
#     server" library), jsdom (DOM emulation), Angular
#     SSR (server-side render), and React Server
#     Components implementations
#
# Cross-language interop happens at the DOM level (parsed
# DOM is structurally identical) but representation
# differs per lane: scraper produces `ego_tree::Tree<Node>`
# (rooted tree of arena-allocated nodes), x/net/html
# produces `*html.Node` (doubly-linked tree), parse5
# produces a JSON-shaped object tree. Cross-lane
# transport requires re-serializing to HTML (or to a
# pivot format like JSON-LD / Markdown).
#
# Axis 242 opens with the Rust slot at the canonical
# Servo-extracted HTML5 parser + the scraper ergonomic
# facade.
# ============================================================================

_docrawl() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '--all[crawl whole same-origin site (ignores --depth)]' \
        '--depth[max link depth from start (default 10)]:N:' \
        '(-o --output)'{-o,--output}'[output root (site folder created inside)]:path:_files -/' \
        '--concurrency[parallel fetch workers (default 16)]:N:' \
        '--rate[global requests/second (default 10)]:N:' \
        '--host-only[restrict scope to exact origin]' \
        '--external-assets[allow downloading images from other domains]' \
        '--allow-svg[permit saving SVG images]' \
        '--max-pages[stop after writing N pages]:N:' \
        '*--selector[preferred content CSS selector (repeatable)]:css:' \
        '*--exclude[URL exclusion regex (repeatable)]:regex:' \
        '--timeout-minutes[graceful shutdown after N minutes]:N:' \
        '--resume[resume from persisted frontier cache]' \
        '--no-assets[skip downloading images/assets (fastest)]' \
        '--fast[preset: higher rate/concurrency + no assets]' \
        '--silence[silence status / progress output]' \
        '--update[self-update from crates.io]' \
        '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[print help]' \
        '(- *)'{-V,--version}'[print version]' \
        '1:starting URL:'
}

_docrawl "$@"
